Specifies what time stamping is applied to the high level data objects which are published as part of the service, e.g. sensor or data collection time, supplier system receipt time or data computation time.

The validity period, after which a high level data object which is published as part of the service can be considered to be no longer valid. A value of zero indicates the objects should be regarded as snapshots in time.

The period during which the availability of the service to the specified standard is defined/guaranteed. This may be by time of day/week/month or other special periods (e.g. 24 h per day every day of the week, excluding national holiday periods).
The mean time to repair the service (MTTR) fault and bring the service back into operation.
The mean time between failures (MTBF) of the service.

The geographic area covered by the service (e.g. specified by a set of bounding coordinate, a regular geometric shape centred on a point or as a named area such as a fuzzy area like a town's industrial area or a tourist area).
The physical coverage of the service (e.g. a list of infrastructure items which are monitored by the service, like a list of roads covered or the types of sensors on specific roads that are covered).

The percentage of physical occurrences which the service is expected to report out of the total actual significant occurrences in the defined coverage range. 100 % implies that the service guarantees to report all significant occurences.
The definition of the coverage of the service in terms of specified business rules (e.g. a traffic flow service only covering vehicles of length > 5,5 m).
A list of one or more types of data which the service will report (e.g. traffic flows, headways, occupancy, travel times, events expected to have a duration of more than 10 minutes, etc.).
Identity of owner of all the data provided by the service.

Specifies whether use of any data provided by the service is restricted. If use is restricted, then the data consumer must refer to the terms and conditions in the agreement with the service provider. Restrictions may be specified in each publication

The probability of the data objects (e.g. event or information records) which are delivered by the service being erroneous relative to the stated accuracy and timeliness. Defined as 1 in 10**x (where x = defined value), max value 10 = infinity.
Identification of the location referencing standard used (e.g. Alert-C, TPEG-Loc, AGORA-C) including any version and date.

The standard against which the spatial data set used for referencing locations has been checked (e.g. reference to the Alert-C Forum validation tool). This is not applicable for on-the-fly location referencing systems.

The type of locations which will be used by the service to locate data objects, i.e. points, linears (including itineraries/routes) or areas (including named and geospatial definitions). A service may use more than one location type.
Identification of where the location information has been obtained from for the service (e.g. road authority, police, civilian, national mapping agency, etc.).

Identification, version and date of the spatial data set used by the service, for example the identity of an Alert-C national data table. This is not applicable for on-the-fly location referencing systems.

The service is absolutely trustworthy and suitable for use where lives, infrastructure or the environment would clearly be put at risk if the service provided erroneous data or failed (e.g. traffic tidal flow systems or access across a railway crossing).
The service is very trustworthy and is suitable for controlling equipments which are critical to the operation of the road network.

The service is generally reliable and is suitable for most control and monitoring operations, but should not be relied upon to control equipment affecting the critical operation of the road network or which control life-threatening situations.
The service is only reliable for monitoring applications and should not be used to controlling equipment.
The service can only be regarded as reliable within the bounds of special conditions defined for the service (e.g. weather conditions may affect the accuracy of certain measurement equipment).
